#compdef mdb
# ============================================================================
#  _mdb — mdb: Mercury Debugger — interactive source-level
#         debugger for Mercury programs (the LOGIC + FUNCTIONAL
#         + STRONGLY-TYPED programming language developed at
#         University of Melbourne)
#         (Mercury Team — Zoltan Somogyi, Fergus Henderson,
#         Thomas Conway et al, with contributions from Mercury
#         community at unimelb.edu.au)
#
#  Source-direct extraction from
#    https://github.com/Mercury-Language/mercury/blob/main/scripts/mdb.in
#      (the mdb shell-wrapper script — flag handling for -t/
#      --tty, -w/--window/--mdb-in-window, --program-in-window,
#      -c/--window-command, --help)
#    https://github.com/Mercury-Language/mercury/blob/main/compiler/options.m
#      (Mercury compiler options — written in Mercury itself
#      using Mercury stdlib `getopt` module; formal Mercury CLI
#      library entry)
#
#  Maintained by Mercury Project (University of Melbourne
#  Programming Languages and Compiler Construction group;
#  Zoltan "zs" Somogyi as principal compiler engineer, Fergus
#  Henderson, Thomas Conway, Peter Schachte, and the broader
#  Mercury community).  Mercury-Language/mercury: 1,056 GH
#  stars (Mercury has been ACTIVELY DEVELOPED SINCE 1995 — over
#  30 years of academic and industrial deployment).  mdb is the
#  INTERACTIVE SOURCE-LEVEL DEBUGGER for Mercury programs —
#  runs a Mercury-compiled executable under the supervision of
#  the Mercury Internal Debugger (MIDB), providing step / next
#  / finish / break / print / where / browse / retry / abort
#  commands familiar to gdb users PLUS Mercury-specific
#  commands for INSPECTING LOGIC VARIABLES (printing unbound
#  variables, tracing unification, examining the proof tree of
#  non-deterministic goals), TIME-TRAVELING through the
#  execution history (`retry` undoes the last call), and
#  DECLARATIVE DEBUGGING (mdb can prompt the user to verify
#  whether a particular goal SHOULD have succeeded; based on
#  the answers, mdb localizes the bug to a specific clause).
#  Sister tools: gdb (GNU Debugger — in corpus + STOCK; the C/
#  C++ equivalent), lldb (LLVM Debugger — in corpus + STOCK
#  macOS), pdb (Python Debugger — in corpus + STOCK Python),
#  rust-gdb (in corpus + STOCK Rust toolchain), R424 Picat
#  (logic+functional language; closest spiritual sister), R443
#  Curry/PAKCS (logic+functional via Prolog backend), prolog/
#  swipl (in corpus + STOCK; pure logic), R429 Frege (Haskell
#  on JVM — closest functional-only relative).
#
#  CLI library taxonomy update: 1st Mercury CLI library —
#  Mercury stdlib **getopt** module (`libs.options.m` uses
#  `:- import_module getopt`).  Mercury joins the cross-
#  language taxonomy as the 39th documented language.  🎉 NEW
#  LANGUAGE entry — Mercury joins alongside Rust, Go,
#  TypeScript-Node, Python, Ruby, Perl, Haskell, OCaml,
#  Elixir, R, Bash, Deno, Lua, Scheme, Clojure, Common Lisp,
#  Racket, Crystal, Nim, Zig, Odin, V, Mojo, Roc, Hare,
#  Standard ML, Erlang, Pony, Prolog, Pike, F#, Janet, D,
#  Picat, BQN, Frege, Lobster, Curry.
#
#  MERCURY is a PURELY DECLARATIVE LOGIC + FUNCTIONAL
#  PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE developed at the University of
#  Melbourne starting 1993.  Distinct from other logic
#  languages (Prolog, Picat, Curry) by being STRONGLY TYPED
#  with HINDLEY-MILNER TYPE INFERENCE + TYPE CLASSES, having
#  MODE DECLARATIONS (each predicate specifies which
#  arguments are inputs vs outputs at each call site,
#  enabling the compiler to generate efficient deterministic
#  code from non-deterministic-looking source), and being
#  DETERMINISM-CHECKED at compile time (the compiler proves
#  that a `det` predicate is in fact deterministic, that a
#  `semidet` can succeed at most once, etc.).  Compiles to C,
#  Java, or C# backends.  Used industrially at GE for medical
#  imaging diagnostics, at Mission Critical IT (a Mercury-
#  focused consultancy spun out of unimelb), and at several
#  finance/insurance/logistics companies for rule-based
#  systems requiring formal correctness guarantees.  Sister
#  tools: PAKCS (R443 — Curry's Prolog-backend impl from
#  CAU Kiel), Picat (R424 — Neng-Fa Zhou's pattern-matching
#  logic+functional+constraint+actor+tabling language),
#  SWI-Prolog (in corpus + STOCK; pure logic).
#
#  Mercury stdlib `getopt` is the CANONICAL CLI library for
#  Mercury — shipped in Mercury's standard library (`getopt`
#  module).  Used by Mercury's own compiler `mmc` (via
#  `compiler/options.m`).  Distinguishing features: PREDICATE-
#  BASED option dispatch — caller defines a PREDICATE
#  `optdb(category, option, option_data, help)` that ENUMERATES
#  all options as Mercury PATTERN-MATCH CLAUSES.  Each clause
#  associates a long-flag-name string (e.g. "verbose"), an
#  optional short-name char (e.g. 'v'), a type (bool / int /
#  string / accumulating string-list / etc.), a default value,
#  and a help-text fragment.  At parse time, Mercury's `getopt`
#  walks argv and dispatches each `-x` / `--name` to the
#  appropriate handler via the `optdb` predicate's pattern
#  matching, accumulating parsed values into an OPTION TABLE
#  (a Mercury `map` from option to `option_data`).  After
#  parsing, the caller queries the option table via
#  `lookup_option/3` / `lookup_string_option/3` /
#  `lookup_bool_option/3` etc.  This API leverages Mercury's
#  PATTERN MATCHING + DETERMINISM ANALYSIS — the compiler
#  proves the option dispatch is exhaustive, that each option
#  has a default, and that the resulting option table is
#  type-correct.  PROOF OF CORRECTNESS is part of the API.
#
#  Mercury getopt API (in Mercury):
#    :- module my_tool.
#    :- interface.
#    :- import_module io.
#    :- pred main(io::di, io::uo) is det.
#
#    :- implementation.
#    :- import_module getopt, list, map, maybe, string.
#
#    % Define the option type — enumeration of all flags
#    :- type option ---> verbose ; output_file ; max_count.
#
#    % Define option dispatch: short name char (or absent)
#    :- pred short_option(char::in, option::out) is semidet.
#    short_option('v', verbose).
#    short_option('o', output_file).
#    short_option('n', max_count).
#
#    % Define long-name strings
#    :- pred long_option(string::in, option::out) is semidet.
#    long_option("verbose", verbose).
#    long_option("output", output_file).
#    long_option("output-file", output_file).
#    long_option("max-count", max_count).
#
#    % Define default values for each option
#    :- pred option_defaults(option::out, option_data::out) is multi.
#    option_defaults(verbose, bool(no)).
#    option_defaults(output_file, string("")).
#    option_defaults(max_count, int(10)).
#
#    main(!IO) :-
#      io.command_line_arguments(Args, !IO),
#      getopt.process_options(
#        option_ops_multi(short_option, long_option, option_defaults),
#        Args, NonOptionArgs, OptionResult),
#      ( OptionResult = ok(OptionTable),
#        getopt.lookup_bool_option(OptionTable, verbose, Verbose),
#        getopt.lookup_string_option(OptionTable, output_file, OutFile),
#        getopt.lookup_int_option(OptionTable, max_count, MaxCount),
#        ... use the parsed values ...
#      ; OptionResult = error(Error),
#        io.write_string("Error: " ++ Error ++ "\n", !IO)
#      ).
#
#  Mercury getopt distinctive features:
#    - PREDICATE-DRIVEN dispatch — each option is defined as
#      multiple Mercury clauses (`short_option`, `long_option`,
#      `option_defaults`) that the compiler proves exhaustive
#      via determinism analysis
#    - DETERMINISM-CHECKED — `:- mode optdb(in, out, out, out)
#      is multi.` declarations force the compiler to verify
#      that the option dispatch covers all cases
#    - TYPE-CORRECT option table — `option_data` is a Mercury
#      DISCRIMINATED UNION (`bool(bool) ; int(int) ; string
#      (string) ; accumulating(list(string)) ; maybe_int(maybe
#      (int)) ; ...`), so the compiler proves that
#      `lookup_int_option` only succeeds on options declared as
#      `int(...)` type
#    - ACCUMULATING flags — `accumulating(list(string))` type
#      means each occurrence of the flag APPENDS to a list
#      (e.g. `-I dir1 -I dir2` accumulates `["dir1", "dir2"]`)
#    - SPECIAL flags — `special(SpecialHandler)` allows custom
#      handlers for flags that don't fit the standard
#      bool/int/string/accumulating pattern (e.g. mmc's
#      `-O <level>` flag triggers a special handler that sets
#      many other optimization-related flags as a side effect)
#    - SECTION-BASED help — options are organized into categories
#      (general, output, optimization, debugging, etc.) for
#      auto-generated help text via `print_help.m`
#    - MULTI-MODE PREDICATES — `:- mode optdb(out, in, out,
#      out) is multi.` allows the option dispatch to be queried
#      in EITHER DIRECTION (forward: option → metadata; backward:
#      iterate all options) thanks to Mercury's multi-mode
#      predicates
#    - INSPIRED BY POSIX getopt_long(3) but enhanced with
#      Mercury's strong-typing + determinism guarantees
#  Mercury's `getopt` is the FIRST DOCUMENTED Mercury CLI
#  library in the corpus's cross-language taxonomy.  Mercury
#  joins the 38 other documented languages as the 39th
#  represented language.  Brings cross-language CLI library
#  taxonomy variant count to 186 (185 + Mercury-getopt = 186).
#
#  Surface (verbatim from `scripts/mdb.in` shell-wrapper case
#  matching):
#
#  Usage:
#    mdb [<options>] <executable> [<args>]...
#
#  Options:
#    -t, --tty <FILE>               Redirect all debugger I/O
#                                   to the device specified by
#                                   <FILE> (typically another
#                                   terminal's /dev/pts/N).
#                                   The program being debugged
#                                   still uses the current
#                                   terminal for its I/O —
#                                   useful for keeping mdb's
#                                   command output separate
#                                   from the program's output
#    -w, --window, --mdb-in-window  Run mdb in a NEW WINDOW
#                                   (typically an xterm), with
#                                   mdb's I/O going to that
#                                   window, but the program's
#                                   I/O going to the current
#                                   terminal.  Note: only works
#                                   on systems with X Window
#                                   System
#        --program-in-window        Run the PROGRAM in a new
#                                   window, with the program's
#                                   I/O going to that window
#                                   but mdb's I/O going to the
#                                   current terminal.  Note:
#                                   stdin/stdout redirection
#                                   will NOT work with this
#                                   option.  Works on most
#                                   UNIX X systems even when
#                                   --mdb-in-window doesn't
#    -c, --window-command <CMD>     Specify the command used
#                                   by --program-in-window for
#                                   executing a command in a
#                                   new window (Default:
#                                   "xterm -e"; use "gnome-
#                                   terminal -e" or "kitty -e"
#                                   for other terminals)
#        --help                     Show mdb usage help and exit
#
#  Positional:
#    <executable>                   Mercury-compiled executable
#                                   to debug.  Must be compiled
#                                   with --debug option to mmc
#                                   for full source-level
#                                   debugging support (otherwise
#                                   only LIMITED debugging
#                                   features are available)
#    <args>...                      Command-line arguments to
#                                   pass to the debugged program
#
#  Environment variables (read by mdb):
#    MERCURY_OPTIONS                Default Mercury runtime
#                                   options applied to the
#                                   debugged executable (e.g.
#                                   --heap-size, --stack-size)
#    MERCURY_DEBUGGER_INIT          Path to mdb's initialization
#                                   script (typically ~/.mdbrc)
#                                   loaded on startup; can
#                                   define aliases, breakpoints
#                                   to set, etc.
#
#  Interactive mdb commands (typed at the `mdb>` prompt after
#  startup — NOT shell CLI flags):
#    Step / next / finish           Single-step / step over /
#                                   run until current call
#                                   returns (gdb-like)
#    break <port> <module:proc>     Set a breakpoint at a
#                                   specific procedure
#    delete <breakpoint-id>         Remove a breakpoint
#    print <var>                    Print value of a Mercury
#                                   logic variable
#    browse <var>                   Interactive browser for
#                                   inspecting structured data
#    retry                          TIME-TRAVEL: undo the last
#                                   call and re-execute from
#                                   before it (unique to logic
#                                   debuggers; possible because
#                                   Mercury programs have no
#                                   side effects in pure code)
#    abort                          Abort the program
#    where                          Show current call stack
#    declarative_debug              Start DECLARATIVE DEBUGGER
#                                   session — mdb prompts user
#                                   to verify whether each
#                                   intermediate goal SHOULD
#                                   have succeeded; based on
#                                   yes/no answers, localizes
#                                   the bug to a specific clause
#    help [<topic>]                 Show help (general or per-
#                                   command)
#    quit                           Exit debugger
#
#  Examples:
#    mdb ./myprogram                                      # Debug myprogram with default I/O
#    mdb -t /dev/pts/2 ./myprogram                        # Send mdb I/O to another terminal
#    mdb -w ./myprogram                                   # Open mdb in new xterm window
#    mdb --program-in-window ./myprogram                  # Open PROGRAM in new window
#    mdb -c "gnome-terminal -e" --program-in-window ./prog
#    mdb ./myprogram arg1 arg2                            # Pass args to debugged program
#    MERCURY_DEBUGGER_INIT=~/.mdbrc mdb ./myprogram       # Custom init script
#    mdb --help                                           # Show mdb usage
#
#  Dup-skipped neighbors during hunt (in corpus or smaller user base,
#  similar Mercury family / academic debuggers):
#    - mercury (IN CORPUS via _mercury — wraps mmc/mmake/mtags;
#      Mercury's main compiler/build/tags tools; previously
#      documented but Mercury language itself not formally
#      entered into taxonomy)
#    - swipl (IN CORPUS via _swipl + STOCK — SWI-Prolog; has
#      its own debugger via `trace.` / `notrace.` commands)
#    - gdb (IN CORPUS + STOCK — GNU Debugger; the C/C++ equivalent)
#    - lldb (IN CORPUS + STOCK macOS — LLVM Debugger)
#    - mldb (Mercury LIBRARY debugger — secondary mdb variant;
#      FUTURE candidate)
#    - mprof / mprof_merge_runs (Mercury profilers; FUTURE
#      candidates)
#    - mdice (Mercury dice — coverage analysis; FUTURE)
#    - merc_doc (Mercury documentation generator; FUTURE)
#    - mfilterjavac (Mercury → Java filter; FUTURE)
#    - Mercury-Language/mercury repo itself (1,056 stars
#      language not CLI)
# ============================================================================

_mdb() {
  local context state state_descr line
  typeset -A opt_args

  _arguments -s -S \
    '--help[show mdb usage help and exit]' \
    '(-t --tty)'{-t,--tty}'[redirect all debugger I/O to specified device]:file:_files' \
    '(-w --window --mdb-in-window)'{-w,--window,--mdb-in-window}'[run mdb in a new window]' \
    '--program-in-window[run the program in a new window]' \
    '(-c --window-command)'{-c,--window-command}'[command to execute in new window]:command:' \
    '*:executable:_files'
}

_mdb "$@"
